{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"86d2a87f-f0ab-4e64-b71b-8ff60fe35af6","content":"On macOS, the OS automatically generates crash reports — no `createdump` needed:\n\n**Crash Reports (always generated):**\n```\n~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n```\nLook for `.ips` or `.crash` files named after your process.\n\n**Core Dumps (opt-in):**\n```bash\nulimit -c unlimited\n# Run your app — core file goes to /cores/\nls /cores/\n```\n\nYou can also open **Console.app → Crash Reports** to browse them with a GUI.\n\nThe `.ips` crash report includes the faulting thread, stack trace, and register state — often enough to diagnose the issue without a full core dump.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"6213d4c1-4024-4c6c-a283-0ec6df52c845","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about how to find crash dumps or crash reports for a NativeAOT app on macOS when `createdump` is not available. This is a knowledge question - I can answer it directly without needing to search the codebase.\n\nOn macOS, when an app crashes, the system generates crash reports automatically. Here's what I know:\n\n1. **macOS Crash Reports** are stored in `~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/` (for user apps) or `/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/` (for system-wide).\n2. You can also use **Console.app** to view them.\n\n\n3. Core dumps can be enabled by setting `ulimit -c unlimited`, which directs them to `/cores/`.\n\nSince NativeAOT doesn't include `createdump` like CoreCLR does, you're working with the OS-level crash reporting mechanisms instead.","outputTokens":412,"requestId":"CB03:3454B1:21D9F23:251F995:6A052985"},"id":"21007ed5-db71-4f03-9575-4288d200f75b","timestamp":"2026-05-14T01:46:55.120Z","parentId":"e6207aa5-9b51-4f66-aabc-a14018730279"}
